- 'Questions' are a type of data point;
- 'Views' are a type of access event;
- The `access_count` is the number of times a data point has been viewed.

- "Most popular data points" refers to data points with the highest access counts;
- "Types of access" include actions such as viewing or downloading the data points;
- "Total number of access events" is the count of all access events for each type of access.

- "definitive answers" refers to accepted answers;
- "measure the time it took for these answers to emerge" refers to the average response time;
- "focusing on those that resonated with immediate attention" means the questions with positive average response times.

- "Seeds of inquiry" refer to questions;
- "Blossoms of questions" represent all questions in the dataset;
- "Unanswered" means questions that have no accepted answers;
- "Time it takes for each to sprout" refers to the average response time for each question;
- "Depth of their roots in the soil of discussion" refers to the level of the question in the hierarchical discussion.

- "Question hierarchy" refers to the structure where questions are organized based on whether they have response times or not;
- "Data points" are the individual items of data that questions are asked about;
- "Categories" are groups that data points belong to;
- "Average response time" is calculated by summing the total response times for all questions in a category and dividing by the number of questions.
